19. A microbiological criterion consists of the following components: 
	6	The purpose of the microbiological criterion; 
	6	The food, process or food safety control system to which the microbiological criterion applies; 
	6	The specified point in the food chain where the microbiological criterion applies; 
	6	The microorganism(s) and the reason for its selection; 
	6	The microbiological limits (m, M; see Section 4.6) or other limits ( e.g. a level of risk);  
	6	A sampling plan defining the number of sample units to be taken ( n), the size of the analytical unit and where appropriate, the acceptance number (c);  
	6	Depending on its purpose, an indication of the statistical performance of the sampling plan; and 
	6	Analytical methods and their performance parameters. 
20. Consideration should be given to the a ction to be taken when the microbiological criterion is not met and the action should be specified (see Section 4.11). 
21. Other considerations could include, but are not limited to, the following: 
	6	Type of sample (e.g. type of food matrix, raw materials, finished product); 
	6	Sampling tools and techniques; 
	6	Prevalence and concentration data for the organism of concern (e.g. baseline data) 
	6	Frequency and timing of sampling; 
	6	Type of sampling (randomized, stratified etc.);  
	6	Methodology used and, when appropriate, suitable conditions for pooling of samples; 
	6	Economic and administrative feasibility, in particular in the choice of sampling plan; 
	6	Interpretation of results;  
	6	Record keeping;  
	6	The intended and actual use of the food; 
	6	The microbiological status of the raw material(s); 
	6	The effect of processing on the microbiological status of the food; 
	6	The likelihood and consequences of microbial contamination and/or growth and inactivation during subsequent handling, packaging, storage, preparation and use; and 
	6	The likelihood of detection. 
22. In addition, for a microbiological criterion targeting a foodborne pathogen, consideration should be given to: 
	6	The evidence of actual or potential risks to health; and 
	6	The population at risk and consumption habits.

